<subSubSection id="C33A651A98115A13DADCFB3AD3FAF9D6" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9F369198115A13DADCFB3AD103FAF4" blockId="13.[189,1399,1200,1301]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6098115A13DADCFB3AD3D6FB2A" author="Bergmans" box="[189,451,1200,1227]" firstAuthor="Bergmans" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="75 - 146" refId="ref257208" refString="Bergmans W. 1988. Taxonomy and biogeography of African fruit bats (Mammalia, Megachiroptera). 1. General introduction; Material and methods; Results: The genus Epomophorus Bennett, 1836. Beaufortia 38 (5): 75 - 146. Available from http: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 548382 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1988">Bergmans (1988: 134)</bibRefCitation>
discussed the status of the two subspecies of 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D1298115A13D9B5FB3AD67CFB2A" baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[980,1129,1200,1226]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wahlbergi">
<emphasis id="B954EA8398115A13D9B5FB3AD67CFB2A" box="[980,1129,1200,1226]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">E. wahlbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and concluded that the size variations are of a clinal nature and the recognition of subspecies does not seem to be appropriate, a view which is also followed by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6098115A13D827FB71D107FAF4" author="Happold" box="[582,786,1274,1300]" firstAuthor="Happold" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="249 - 251" refId="ref262839" refString="Happold M. 2013 c. Epomophorus wahlbergi Wahlberg's Epauletted Fruit Bat. In: Happold M. &amp; Happold D. (eds) Mammals of Africa Volume IV. Hedgehogs, Shrews and Bats: 249 - 251. Bloomsbury Publishing, London." type="book chapter" year="2013" yearSuffix="c">Happold (2013c)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9F369198115A13DADCFAB6D3FAF9D6" blockId="13.[189,1399,1341,1590]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
The records in 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6098115A13DB13FAB5D08AFAB8" author="Hayman" box="[370,671,1341,1368]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Hayman" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="1 - 105" refId="ref265860" refString="Hayman R. W., Misonne X. &amp; Verheyen W. N. 1966. The bats of the Congo and of Rwanda and Burundi. Annalen van het Koninklijk Museum voor Midden Afrika, Zoologische Wetenschappen, Ser. 8, 154: 1 - 105." type="journal article" year="1966">
Hayman 
<emphasis id="B954EA8398115A13DBBFFAB5D00EFAB8" box="[478,539,1342,1368]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">et al.</emphasis>
(1966: 24)
</bibRefCitation>
were primarily from the southern half of the 
<collectingCountry id="F337760198115A13DEA0FAB5D715FAB8" box="[1217,1280,1342,1368]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">DRC</collectingCountry>
, with two specimens from Rutshuru (Nord-Kivu Province - INPBC 
<date id="FF9E105198115A13D90AFAE9D1AEFA9C" box="[875,955,1378,1404]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1346-05">V1346</date>
and 
<date id="FF9E105198115A13D997FAE9D65FFA9D" box="[1014,1098,1378,1405]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" value="1636-05">V1636</date>
), and one specimen from Ibembo (Bas-Uélé Province - RMCA 20278). The additional material we report on, is also from the southern part of the 
<collectingCountry id="F337760198115A13DBD7FA26D3E0FA27" box="[438,501,1453,1479]" name="Democratic Republic of the Congo" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">DRC</collectingCountry>
, but also from the Nord-Kivu and South-Kivu Provinces, as well as from 
<collectingCountry id="F337760198115A13DADCFA59D308FA0C" box="[189,285,1490,1516]" name="Burundi" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Burundi</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry id="F337760198115A13DB00FA59D3D0FA0C" box="[353,453,1490,1516]" name="Rwanda" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Rwanda</collectingCountry>
. The locality of a further central Congolese specimen (RMCA 18844b from Bokungu in Tshuapa Province) is rather unexpected, as 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB14B6098115A13D92EFA7CD642F9F1" author="Bergmans" box="[847,1111,1527,1553]" firstAuthor="Bergmans" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="75 - 146" refId="ref257208" refString="Bergmans W. 1988. Taxonomy and biogeography of African fruit bats (Mammalia, Megachiroptera). 1. General introduction; Material and methods; Results: The genus Epomophorus Bennett, 1836. Beaufortia 38 (5): 75 - 146. Available from http: // www. repository. naturalis. nl / document / 548382 [accessed 29 Nov. 2017]." type="journal article" year="1988">Bergmans (1988: 131)</bibRefCitation>
stated that 
<taxonomicName id="4C204D1298115A13DEBEFA7CD762F9F1" baseAuthorityName="Sundevall" baseAuthorityYear="1846" box="[1247,1399,1527,1553]" class="Mammalia" family="Pteropodidae" genus="Epomophorus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="wahlbergi">
<emphasis id="B954EA8398115A13DEBEFA7CD762F9F1" box="[1247,1399,1527,1553]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">E. wahlbergi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not found moist forests.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
